File transfer with s-c-p and rsync.

There are two main tools for copying files between machines, and both run over s-s-h, which means they inherit all of its authentication, encryption, and key setup for free. The first is s-c-p, secure copy. It works just like the ordinary copy command but across machines, with the same source-then-destination syntax; you simply prefix a remote path with a username, a host, and a colon. So you can push a local file up to a remote path, pull a remote file down, copy a whole directory recursively, or even copy between two remote hosts. One small gotcha: to set a custom port, s-c-p uses a capital dash-p, unlike the lowercase one s-s-h uses. S-c-p is simple and available everywhere, but for anything beyond a few files, rsync is the better tool.

Rsync is what you reach for when you want serious copying. It does incremental syncs, transferring only the files that changed, and even only the changed parts of those files. It can resume an interrupted transfer where it left off. It can keep two directory trees identically mirrored, and it is far faster than s-c-p for repeated backups. The basic form gives it a source and a destination, with one of them possibly remote.

A few flags carry most of the weight. Dash a is archive mode, which is really a bundle of options that copy recursively while preserving permissions, timestamps, and ownership. Dash v is verbose, dash z compresses during the transfer to save bandwidth, and dash capital-p shows progress and keeps partial files so an interrupted run can resume. The delete option also removes files on the destination that no longer exist on the source, giving you a true mirror, and the dry-run option shows you exactly what would happen without actually doing it. One subtlety to remember with rsync is the trailing-slash rule on the source: a source path with a trailing slash copies the contents of the directory, while one without the slash copies the directory itself.
